                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d200">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">462.00R296/4997: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Minister in Yugoslavia</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Prince</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-08-26T17:00:00-04:00"
                            >August 26, 1931—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>17. Your 39, August 22, 11 a.m. You may if you consider it necessary inform the
                    King that his message has been brought to the attention of the President and
                    reaffirm at the same time the substance of the Department’s No. 16, August 25, 5
                    p.m.</p>
                <p>You will of course bear in mind during any conversations that you may have with
                    the King that while this Government would welcome any satisfactory arrangement
                    whereby Yugoslavia might see its way clear to participate in the debt suspension
                    plan, the Department desires you scrupulously to refrain from giving any
                    encouragement to the apparent impression of the Yugoslav authorities that a
                    solution of this question is in any way incumbent upon this Government.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Castle</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
